    <id>https://doi.org/10.1177/10591478261461411</id>
    <title>EXPRESS: Operations and Supply Chain Management in China: Part I - a New Analytical Model and Academic Progress</title>
    <updated>2026-06-06T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Desheng Wu</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;Production and Operations Management&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;This paper analyzes the academic evolution and educational progress of Operations and Supply Chain Management (OSCM) in China. The field has transformed over recent decades. It has transitioned from a knowledge-importing phase to indigenous innovation. We show that China has built a massive educational infrastructure and research system. This study proposes an innovative Institutional-Dynamic-Organizational (IDO) model to systematically evaluate this trajectory. Historical bibliometric data analysis from top-tier journals reveals a sharp shift in research momentum. Publications by China-based scholars in frontier domains grew dramatically. This academic evolution analytics offers profound contributions and actionable insights for Western economies and global supply chain systems.</content>
